Ok real talk no bs now Decline bench is the most underrated chest exercise. Probably best bench variation. The "it trains your lower chest" is broscience mythology, for many people it hits upper chest better than incline. Lowest chance of shoulder injury. Massive triceps builder.

It's basically what regular bench should be and why people arch so much, you're pre-arched here. No overtraining from your front delts taking over and imbalances. Literally perfect leverages which is why you can push more weight than flat bench. Easily breaks you out of plateus.

If you're stuck just endlessly benching 2 plates for 5-6 reps for months with no progress you can load that on the decline and rep it for a 12 rep set and start adding weight. If you plateau in a few weeks going back to flat/incline weights will feel lighter due to mental magic

This happened to Varg Vikernes as a child in a skiing incident, where he watched himself from above falling from a cliff before re-entering his body and suddenly sensing the pain of broken bones, bleeding in the cold, etc.

Rare thread from me. The good baron Julius Evola described how man's soul is able to exit his body through the heart's ventricle and how this can be induced under extreme torture. This protects the torture victim's soul from experiencing the pain the body is under.

I think surgical NDEs are often something similar, e.g. patients seeing the surgeons operating on them in the room from above etc. Anesthesia turns off consciousness, memory, but the brain still gets the massive stress signals from the surgery and interprets it as injury, pain.

I believe this method would probably greatly reduce the rate of those anecdotes of patients seeing the doctors operating from above the table. A lot of the time it's probably not just NDE but tremendous pain that imitates being tortured causing the soul to flee the sensing body.

Dr. Peat said the ideal surgery would involve Scopolamine and using a ton of Lidocaine, slowly slicing the skin layer by layer and constantly applying topical lidocaine so the local stress signals are never produced and the brain doesn't understand what's going on there at all.

This would be a truly interdisciplinary study and seems out of the scope of current medicine ofc. To make it a bit more fun: Varg Vikernes murdered Euronymous because he threatened to kidnap Varg and torture him to death in the forest. If we remember Varg's ski anecdote, this...

"... cheek; but our principle is instead doing to others what they would like to do to us: but doing it first, before they are able to." Varg's actions against Euronymous perfectly fit with this to a degree that I find funny. Remember. Scopolamine. Novocaine. Divine substances.

... would have probably triggered Varg's soul again doing the same and exiting his body due to the pain, as he has that pre-disposition already, making it more likely to manifest again. To finish this Evola said something of the sort of "Our principle is not giving the other..."

I have mentioned all of these already but I keep drawing new connections between the books of Seraphim Rose on "the soul after death", Dr. Ana Aslan's research with painkillers, Agrippa's occult works. It's obviously all related and flows into each other.

Someone posted an excerpt from Heidegger where he talks about an anecdote out of Antiquity. How some young Greek students went to visit Heraclitus in his home and when they were at his doorstep they saw him warming himself at an oven and they stopped there instead of entering.

He told them "the gods are also here" or such words, prompting them to enter. Heidegger's explanation was that they wanted to see Heraclitus in a dramatic pose, engaged in deep philosophic thinking, so they were confused by how strange it was seeing him doing regular house stuff.

It reminds you of Mishima where the young boy is scandalized by finding his mother's boyfriend, the sailor, being wet due to having bathed at the fountain instead of it being due to jumping in the sea to save some woman, doing something heroic. Betrayal of the ideal by mundanity.

Heidegger's point I believe was that philosophy is something you do as labor, not unlike a farmer's work, it's something a farmer does while doing his farm work. Basically that philosophy means warming yourself at the oven and not sitting in dramatic thinking poses.

Recently a friend translated this Salvador Dali interview where he talks about hating Auguste Rodin's "The Thinker" statue because it shows a dramatic philosophical posture that Dali finds unbearable. It seems very related to Mishima and to Heraclitus and the young students.

I myself like Dali, Rodin, Heidegger, Heraclitus, Mishima, etc. all very much. It's interesting to think about this issue. Second thread tonight because I had fermented food and kept my body in a cold room after a warm bath so I am verbose and can't contain myself to one post.
